<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="supp-historigdate" xml:lang="en">
    <head>Original date of text and/or object</head>
    <p>The date of origin of the text (or in some cases, of the object or some other feature, decoration, or reuse of it),
    whether the result of the editor's analysis or an explicit, internal date. May also record possible ranges of dates,
    degrees of precision and dating criteria.</p>
    
    <p><specList>
        <specDesc key="origDate"/>
        <specDesc key="precision"/>
    </specList></p>
    
    <p>
        The date of orgin of the text (or object, if different) should be recorded in an <gi>origDate</gi> element
        in the <gi>origin</gi> section of the manuscript description area. If different dates need to be recorded
        for text and object, different texts on the same support, or different interventions in the same text, the
        <gi>origDate</gi> may be repeated, or the entire <gi>history</gi> may be embedded in multiple
        <gi>msPart</gi>s.
    </p>
    
    <p>
        It is generally recommended to encode the dating information in numerical form, following the 
        proleptic Julian calendar, using the att.datable.custom attributes on the <gi>origDate</gi> element.
        (Because the default dating system assumed by the TEI is the Gregorian calendar, the dating element
        should always carry a <att>datingMethod</att> attribute pointing to a <gi>calendar</gi> element in the
        header--or to an external authority for the Julian calendar, such as
        <ref>http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julian_calendar</ref>.)
    </p>
    
    <p>
        attributes...
    </p>
    
    <p>... basic dating, including ranges/spans, with examples ...</p>
    
    <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
        <origDate when-custom="0139" datingMethod="#Julian">139 C.E.</origDate>
    </egXML>
    <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
        <origDate notBefore-custom="-0420-12-11" notAfter-custom="-0419-12-10" datingMethod="#Julian">
            December 11th, 420 to December 10th, 419 B.C.E.
        </origDate>
    </egXML>
    
    <div>
        <head>Precision</head>
        <p>... including different precision for notBefore/notAfter; medium=block dates, low=circa ...</p>
        
        <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
            <origDate notBefore-custom="-0100" notAfter-custom="0100" precision="medium" datingMethod="#Julian">
                First century B.C. to first century A.D.
            </origDate>
        </egXML>
        
        <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
            <origDate when-custom="-0355" precision="low" datingMethod="#Julian">
                Circa 355 B.C.E.
            </origDate>
        </egXML>
        
        <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
            <origDate notBefore-custom="0015" notAfter-custom="0050" datingMethod="#Julian">
                First half first century C.E., but certainly after the death of Augustus.
                <precision match="../@notAfter-custom" precision="low"/>
                <precision match="../@notBefore-custom" precision="high"/>
            </origDate>
        </egXML>
    </div>
    
    <div>
        <head>Dating criteria</head>
        <p>... @evidence, suggest typology, example values ...</p>
        
        <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
            <origDate notBefore-custom="0367" notAfter-custom="0400" precision="medium" evidence="lettering nomenclature" datingMethod="#Julian">
                Late fourth century (lettering and nomenclature).
            </origDate>
        </egXML>
    </div>
    
